beer_description: Brewed with two-row malt, Munich malt, dark roasted caramel, and chocolate malts, this Doppelbock is based on the beer that won a silver medal at the Great American Beer Festival. A deep, auburn brown hue hints at the complex caramel malt taste, accented by its big body, slightly spicy and sweet aftertaste, and softly hopped finish. It is a thick but balanced and drinkable dark lager, well aged. Hopped with Northern Brewer and Tettnang.

Tawny brown with glints of red and copper. It is mildly carbonated with subtle touches of sherry and nutty flavors, slightly sweet and fruity, mellow and only slightly bitter in the finish. An exceptionally smooth brown ale, brewed with chocolate, black and caramel malts, and hopped with Northern Brewer, Fuggles, and Willamette hops.

Harttung was one of the first Chicago brewers to serve this wheat beer, which originated in Berlin as a delicious "lady's beer," carbonated and topped with a delicate, snowy mousse of foam. It is served with a splash of raspberry syrup to counteract the astringency and sourness due to it's lactic fermentation. It is made with 30-percent wheat malts, about 70-percent barley malts, and only a small amount of Hallertauer hops for aroma.

So opaque that light barely filters through a glass full of this dark stout. It is a full-bodied, bittersweet ale, with a pleasantly lingering aftertaste that makes a wonderful complement to seafood or grilled vegetables. Its roasted malt character is in good balance with the more assertive hops, such as Northern Brewer, Fuggles, and Willamette. A small amount of oats, added to the wort, helps produce a creamy mouth feel and smoothness.

With its sherry-colored brown and malt aroma, this Oktoberfest calls for some chocolate, caramel, and wheat malts, accented by Hallertauer and Tettnang hops. Full, flowery aromatic noble hops are balanced by the big malt flavor. A seasonal favorite.

A filtered weiss beer with the bubbly Champagne character, know as Kristall in Austria and Germany. It is a low-alcohol, light and refreshing beer. The 40-percent wheat malts used to brew the beer make it crisp, and slighly tart in the finish. Just a pinch of Hallertauer hops are used to aromatize the beer.

Brewed with a selection of two-row malt, Munich malt, caramel and chocolate malts, this rich, coppery-red ale possesses both deep-roasted malt flavor and highly aromatic, almost flowery hops in the nose. Smooth and mellow in the finish. Hopped with Northern Brewer, Fuggles, and Cascade.

Bold British ale flavor from a robust blend of caramel, chocolate and crystal malts, is balanced with the blended aroma of Fuggles, Goldings, Northern Brewer and Cascade hops. The clean hops bitterness softens at the finish, thanks to some residual sweetness and fine carbonation in this bronze-colored ale.

A Bavarian hefe-weiss style, with the special yeast that brings out spicy hints of clove, apple, and banana flavors. It is often served with a lemon. This light, quenching brew is made with 40-percent wheat malt, 60 percent barley malts. Mildly hopped with small amounts of Tettnang and Halleertauer, the "noble" aroma hops of Germany, to accent the spicy aroma of the yeast.

Brewed with two-row malt, Munich malt and carapils, this sparkling, light golden pilsner has a slight malt sweetness at the forefront, followed by a nicely biting effervescence, gentle dryness and full hops flavor. Presented in the traditional fluted Pilsner glass, this straw-colored beer is capped by a lovely, thick white collar of foam, thanks to the judicious use of wheat malt. Hopped with Northern Brewer and Saaz.
The Brewer's special blend of four unique malts including chocolate and caramel malt. A light taste of coffee with a sweet finish makes this one of our best selling beers.

This medium bodied beer is amber to copper in color. The taste is a sweet caramel malt flavor, and is moderately hopped. Traditionally an Irish recipe, our amber beer uses four different barleys with an ample supply of caramel malt.

Premium pale beer, similar to the Bohemian pilsner style, but sweeter and heavier in body. The taste is more malty and less hoppy with smooth undertones. This recipe is near and dear to the Brewer's heart, it was his father's recipe, a 1950 Coal miner from West Virginia. It has been changed ever so slightly to meet today's standard of brewing.
This beer is made with equal parts of wheat, 2 row and 6 row barley. Using a free rise method of fermentation gives this beer a mild summery finish.

A technique developed by the brewmaster, using an extremely long boil and lager yeast makes this beer uniquely distinctive. South German style wheat beer gently hopped, light in body with a sweet finish. This is one of our mildest beers.

Our classic German style Maibock. Rich, full bodied, deep golden-blonde lager. Brewed with the finest 2-row barley and a subtle amount of noble hops, giving it the perfect balance of malty sweetness and hop character
This is Chicago's Original Craft Beer, made from the original recipe and yeast strain.  A Czech style pilsener, full bodied and hop-forward with a malty caramel finish.

ABV varies from 8-10%.

The malty sweetness, fruitiness, unique hop aroma and high original gravity of Old Foghorn? Barleywine Style Ale is to beer much as port is to wine. 

Old Foghorn? is brewed based on traditional English barleywine methods. It is highly hopped, fermented with a true top-fermenting ale yeast, carbonated by a natural process called "bunging" to produce champagne-like bubbles, and dry-hopped with additional Cascade hops while it ages in our cellars. Made only from ?first wort,? the rich first runnings of an all-malt mash, three mashes are required to produce just one barleywine brew.

Introduced in 1975, Old Foghorn? Ale was the first modern American barleywine sparking renewed interest domestically and in Britain. The name was derived from the English tradition of attaching the word ?old? to barleywines to denote their tradition, intensive brewing process and cellar aging, and ?Foghorn? gave it a San Francisco flair. Today, Old Foghorn? Ale is best enjoyed sipped after a meal.
Deep roasted malt from a clever blend of malts, hints of caramel, liquorice & raisin spice. A toasty dryness from pinhead oats with a subtle finish.

Leinenkugel?s Original is brewed with Pale malts and Cluster hops inspired by our family?s 1867 recipe. Its crisp, classic flavor has been carrying the Leinenkugel name for five generations. Bronze Award winner in 1988 for American Premium Pilsners and 1998 Bronze Award winner for American-Style Premium Lager at the Great American Beer Festival?.
Old Style is a beer that revives the crisp rich freshness of a classic Pilsner: light in color and body, medium in aroma and bitterness, full flavored with a delicate aftertaste.

We've already told you that our family never does anything the way other people do. Kriek Lindemans is a good example of that.


In order to obtain a beer like no other, we have been adding whole sour cherries to our lambic for generations.


Our meeting with American importer Charles Finkel in the 1970s revolutionised the fruit beer segment. Charles convinced us to export our old kriek to the United States by boat. What we had not thought of is that the movement of the waves would reactivate the fermentation process and cause the corks to pop during the trip. It was like something out of The Adventures of Tintin. To prevent that from happening, we therefore developed an alternative production method for our kriek. We use fresh, not from concentrate, unsweetened cherry filtrate which we blend with lambic that is at least one year old before fermenting & macerating for up to 3 days and pasteurising the whole batch. So the corks don't pop.


Due to the use of filtrate and pasteurisation, this kriek is sweeter and fruitier than Old Kriek Cuv?e Ren?, which undergoes a second fermentation process in the bottle. Thanks to its innovative flavour, it was a resounding success both here in Belgium as well as around the world. Nowadays, it is undoubtedly the reference kriek for consumers.
This easy drinking velvety porter is brewed with dark-roasted malts. When poured, its deep garnet color is crowned with a creamy tan head.

Yes that's Backus, not Bacchus, named after our good friend Richie Backus. Barleywines are an English style ale of great strength. The huge amounts of both hops and malt that go into this beer necessitate a long conditioning period to mellow its intense flavors. A complex beer that should be savored, not slammed, Old Backus has been rated one of the world?s best barleywines on Ratebeer.com with an overall score of 100.  Despite it?s relative youth Old Backus exhibits a tremendous restraint, balance, and drinkability. Hopped with Columbus and Crystal hops, the Old Backus tops out at near 10% ABV.

beer_description: This is a classic Irish style stout that possesses an initial malt sweetness and caramel flavor with a distinctive dry-roasted bitterness in the finish. Capped by a formidable light brown head, a full-bodied feel is apparent throughout this deep, rich brew.

Classic lager yeast fermentation, 100% domestic malted barley, brew house hopped, brewed with an infusion mash using traditional brewing skills with minimal agitation
to enhance aging nuances.
A real hefe-weizen, with the creamy goodness of wheat, plus a fruity and spicy nose.

Kosmos Spoetzl knew how to brew great beer. Born in Bavaria, Kosmos??? mastery of German brewing carried him as far as Egypt before he found his way to the small Texas town of Shiner. Our proud brewery still carries his name and commitment to excellence in brewing. This full-flavored, hop-jacked lager is every bit as unique as the man himself and our way of saluting the brewmaster who started it all.

A GABF Gold Medal winner for 2007, this Belgian style strong ale, bright and golden colored is brewed with a hint of orange peel and coriander. This balanced, pleasant to drink brew, will sneak up on you. Consume with caution.

At Saint Arnold, we are passionate about animal rescue. A number of us here are proud to have rescue animals as family members. To this end, we are donating a portion of the sales of Ale Wagger to support local rescue organizations to improve the lives of animals in our communities.

A beautiful, deep copper brown ale. It has a full, malty body with hints of chocolate, a touch of sweetness and a light hop flavor. A complex malt character is created by combining five different types of malts. It has a rich, creamy head with a fine lace. The light fruitiness, characteristic of ales, is derived from a proprietary yeast strain.

Saint Arnold Ale Wagger Brown is best consumed at 45-50? Fahrenheit.

Awards:
Bronze Medal, Great American Beer Festival, English-Style Brown Ale, 2003
Silver Medal, World Beer Championships, Brown Ale, 1998
Gold Medal, All American Brew Fest, Brown Ale, 1997
Silver Medal, World Beer Cup, American Brown Ale, 1996
Silver Medal, World Beer Championships, Brown Ale, 1996
1st Place - Colorado State Fair, Brown Ale, 1995
Rainbow Red Ale is auburn in color, with sublte fruity tones and a complex, caramel-like malt flavor. Rainbow red is generously hopped to achieve a crisp taste and delicate bouquet.

Skull Splitter is our strongest ale: which is named after Thorfinn Einarsson who was the 7th Viking Earl of Orkney. Sophisticated, satiny smooth with a deceptively light character, it is a tribute to our colourful forbear.

On the nose, this strong beer has a fruity malt character, with hints of dark fruit, spicy hop, dates and figs.

On the palate, rich and complex with sweet toasted malt, molasses, fresh and dried fruit and hints of warming spices.

The Original Craft Beer; brewed in Scotland since 2000 B.C. The Brotherhood have been guardians of the ancient Gaelic recipe for "leann fraoich" (heather ale) since 1988 and are proud to be the only brewery still producing this unique style of beer and distributing it world wide.  A light amber ale with floral peaty aroma, full malt character, and a spicy herbal finish - This beer allows you to literally pour 4000 years of Scottish history into a glass.

The beer that helped build our brewery; Bell?s Amber Ale features both toasted and sweet caramel notes from carefully selected malts, balanced with herbal and citrus hop aromas. Capped by a clean bitterness, it?s incredibly versatile with food, but very tasty on its own.
Finnish lager with 4,5%

Our golden-yellow wheat beer, with its fine-pored white foam, smells of cloves and impresses consumers with its refreshing banana flavour. It is full bodied and with a smooth yeast taste. To be enjoyed at any time (always a pleasure / enjoyment), goes excellently with fish and seafood, with spicy cheese and especially with the traditional Bavarian veal sausage. Brewed according to our centuries-old brewing tradition on the Weihenstephan hill.

brewery.brewery_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company

beer_description: This American Pale Ale is our flagship brand, celebrating hop bitterness and aroma.  Dry-hopping with three different varieties in the fermenter gives our Paddy it's signature hop-forward bite and rich "nose''.

Old Speckled Hen is in pubs and bars across the country in cask and also as a smooth version at 4.5% ABV.

You can also enjoy ?Old Speckled Hen? in 500ml or 355ml bottles and 500ml cans at 5% ABV from all leading supermarkets and convenience outlets. And for the jet setters amongst us, you can even find it in 47 countries around the world, from Australia to the UAE.

?Old Speckled Hen? has a full, smooth flavour and is very easy to drink. Its rich amber colour and superb fruity aromas are complemented by a delicious blend of malty tastes. Toffee and malt combine with bitterness on the back of the tongue to give a balanced sweetness. This, all followed by a refreshingly dry finish.

beer_description: Our Spring seasonal is a deep golden lager with a flavorful but smooth malt presence. When you see our Maibock hit the shelves you know things are about to get better...including the weather!

The quintessential summer seasonal beer. The wheat gives it a light, zesty taste with notes of banana and clove in the finish. Some yeast is intentionally left behind after partially filtering the beer to give the brew its characteristically cloudy appearance.
Eight malts add depth and complexity, while English hops contribute a refreshing balance to this crisp and drinkable mild brown ale - a true "session" brew.

St-Louis Premium Gueuze contains a blend of young and old lambics. It is a thirst-quencher with a great balance between sourness, typical of geuze, sweet and slightly bitter flavours. Its touches of fruit, including citrus, draw the attention.
Belgian Lambic. 100% spontaneously fermented ale aged for 2 years in oak casks, blended with a top fermented wheat ale. Dry and hoppy in flavor with subtle hints of spice.

For the 6.5% version from tap, please check into https://untappd.com/b/brouwerij-corsendonk-corsendonk-bruin/967386

Marketed as Corsendonk Abbey Brown Ale in North America.
Launched 1982 by Jef Keersmaekers as Pater Noster. Brewed by Brasserie Du Bocq since launch. 
Ingredients: Caramel, Pilsen and Munich barley malts, and Saaz, Kent and Hallertau hops
Brewed with roasted malt, hence its deep dark reddish colour. It is a mellow, dark, top-fermented beer, refermented and matured in the bottle to obtain a lively, bubbly beer with a rich head.
beer_name: Corsendonk Pater Dubbel / Abbey Brown Ale

beer_description:
Liefmans Goudenband is one of the most distinctive dark beers in the world. Originally called IJzerenband (Iron Band) ? a reference to the iron bands around the beer barrels ? the bottle gained its champagne cork when it was renamed Liefmans Goudenband (Gold Band). Made in open vats with beer of mixed fermentation, it is left to mature for four to 12 months in the cellar. Mature beer is then fortified with younger beer, so the fermentation process starts up again.

Liefmans Goudenband is a beer for storing, and just keeps improving over the years like a fine wine. Even after ten years, this dark red beer tastes as fresh as ever. You?ll immediately pick up on the wonderful aromas of caramel, apple, rhubarb, cherries and malt. On the taste buds you will find hints of apple and cherries, combined with woody notes, while the aftertaste hints at nuts and dried raisins. The mildly acidic taste make this beer a perfect match for blue cheese.
A recipe gone untouched since Big Rock's founding. Toasty malt and sweet caramel up front, finished with a nutty flavour, medium creamy carbonation and mild hop bitterness.

A pioneer in craft beer (hey, that rhymes), Summit EPA has been gracing the pint glasses of serious brew lovers since 1986. Bronze color. Gold medal-winning flavor. With caramel, biscuity malts superbly balanced with an earthy hop bite and juicy citrus.

Prairie Path Ale is a Belgian-style golden ale. Prairie Path Ale is a full flavored, slightly bitter, clean and refreshing ale. The Belgian malts along with the Saaz and Goldings hops give this beer great drinkability.
